"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449737","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>We are investing in apprenticeships to meet identified skill needs across all sectors. We are committed to reaching 3 million apprenticeship starts in England by 2020 and will ensure they deliver the skills employers and the economy need for growth. We have also announced plans for ground-breaking reforms to technical and professional education, working in direct partnership with employers to ensure the new system provides the skills most needed for the 21st century. Together with creating 5 National Colleges, supporting a new network of Institutes of Technology and rolling out more degree and higher level apprenticeships, we are helping to equip people with the higher and technical level skills that are in demand.</p><p> </p><p>Our aim is for all local areas to take a leading role in skills provision to ensure it is responsive to local economic priorities and devolution deals with areas around the country are a big step towards this ambition so that they can secure the training and skills that local employers need.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-09T15:37:00.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449737/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449737/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Skilled Workers: Vacancies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they intend to take in response to the skill shortages and consequent unfilled vacancies highlighted in the UK Commission for Employment and Skills Survey 2015 published on 28 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL5819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449738","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>The Teach First programme aims to raise levels of pupil attainment in challenging schools. Since it was founded, Teach First has trained over 5,000 teachers in England, with a further 1,622 starting training in 2015, covering every region of the country.</p><p>Figures supplied to the Department by Teach First show that 1,206 trainees started the two-year leadership development programme in schools in September 2013. Of those, 544<sup>[1]</sup> are known to be still teaching in state-funded schools in England in September 2015.</p><p>Additionally, the Teach First programme has acted as a positive springboard for participants to continue their commitment to the education sector; a number of trainees from this cohort have remained in the education industry in wider roles including outside the classroom, in charities and overseas. Data provided by Teach First in December 2015 shows that 69%<sup>[1]</sup> of the participants who had completed the two-year programme are known to be in teaching or in these wider educational roles.</p><p>[1] Only participants that choose to become Ambassadors for Teach First are tracked in relation to future employment. A total of 1,041 participants completed the two year programme; of these 981 chose to become Ambassadors for Teach First, and by doing so, were tracked in relation to future employment.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-03-03T15:47:21.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449738/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449738/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-02","Teachers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of those who started with Teach First in August 2013 were still teaching in state-funded schools in England in September 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL5820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449739","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-10","<p>Network Rail will be responsible for undertaking works on their network where they interact with the HS2 network. The materials used for such works will be subject to future procurements. However, currently, around 95% of Network Rail’s total aggregated demand for steel is procured from Tata steel.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-02-10T12:03:42.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449739/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449739/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-02","High Speed 2 Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what role Network Rail has in the HS2 project, and whether it will have a role in deciding where the steel required for that project should be purchased from.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL5821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449742","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-09","<p>As part of the Department’s change programme, BIS2020, we anticipate reducing the number of our locations from more than 80 to approximately 7 centres plus a regional footprint. Beyond the announcement made about our Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place on 28 January, we do not yet know exactly which sites will be retained or closed over the course of the Parliament. By 2020 the majority of employees in BIS and its Partner Organisations will continue to be based outside London through a number of centres – such as in Birmingham, Glasgow, and Swindon – as well as a regional footprint for the provision of local services.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-09T17:16:57.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449742/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449742/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what plans he has for his Department's offices in Manchester.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","25330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449743","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>“BIS 2020: What-why-when-how” (September 2015) was one of a series of internal briefings for BIS staff. Staff are briefed on our change programme on a regular basis. The briefings are not formal documents and, as such, we do not publish them.</p><p> </p><p>The House was informed about the recent BIS 2020 announcements and their impact on BIS staff by my Rt hon Friend the Minister of State for Small Business, Industry and Enterprise (Anna Soubry) on Friday 29 January.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-10T16:47:29.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449743/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449743/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will publish in full his Department's report entitled, BIS 2020: What-why-when-how.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449744","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>Since summer 2015, the Department has been reviewing its business model. By 2020, we want to simplify our structure, become more digital, be cheaper for taxpayers and better for users. As part of this we anticipate reducing the number of our locations from more than 80 to approximately 7 centres plus a regional footprint.</p><p> </p><p>BIS2020 is a rolling programme that will be delivered through a number of different strands of the Department’s work.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-10T16:19:52.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449744/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449744/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to announce the full implementation plan for his Department's BIS 2020 strategy.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449745","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>Apprenticeships are categorised according to the Sector Subject Area of the apprenticeship, not the industry sector of the employer.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not produce forecasts for apprenticeship starts by Sector Subject Area. Apprenticeships are paid jobs and their availability is dependent on employers offering opportunities and hiring apprentices.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","25361","2016-02-10T16:29:50.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449745/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449745/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Construction: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many apprenticeship starts there were in each construction occupational area in 2015.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","25360"
