"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449762","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>The financing and borrowing arrangements for the proposed Hinkley Point C nuclear plant have not yet been signed. These arrangements are commercially sensitive and will not be published. However, the Chancellor did announce in September 2015 an initial guarantee of £2 billion of bonds which must be repaid by December 2020 by the shareholders of the project company. There is no further obligation to issue guarantees after that date.</p><p> </p><p>It is the intention of DECC to publish the Contract for Difference following its signature, and this is the document that contains the reduction in the Hinkley Point C “Strike Price” from £92.50 to £89.50 – which is linked to a positive decision by EDF to proceed with Sizewell C.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-08T16:42:44.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449762/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449762/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Hinkley Point C Power Station: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish all agreements made to date with EDF energy over financing and borrowing arrangements for the proposed Hinkley C nuclear plant; and if he will ensure that agreements which relate to the differential financial arrangements depending on development of the Flamanville nuclear plant in France and the proposed Sizewell C plant are so published.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","25454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449763","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-10","<p>The majority of the government’s public debt is financed through the issuance of UK government bonds, known as ‘gilts’. Information on sectoral holdings of gilts is published on a quarterly basis by the Office for National Statistics (ONS).</p><p> </p><p>The latest figures show that £426.9 billion of gilts (25.9% of the total stock) is held by overseas investors, of which £73.3 billion is held by foreign central banks. The government does not hold detailed information on the identity of foreign central banks or other individual investors holding these gilts.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-10T12:42:32.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449763/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449763/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Public Sector Debt: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the UK's outstanding public debt obligations are to China.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","25447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449764","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>Details of Ministers' and Senior Civil Servants' meetings with external organisations, including senior media figures, are published routinely and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications</a> on Gov.uk.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-09T15:42:10.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449764/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449764/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Treasury: Sky","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings (a) Ministers and (b) civil servants in his Department have had with (i) James Murdoch and (ii) representatives from Sky UK Limited in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","25376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449765","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>In the Sukuk structure, rental payments provide the income for investors. When the Sovereign Sukuk were issued in July 2014 the profit rate was set at 2.036% in line with the yield on gilts of similar maturity, making the investor return on the Sukuk broadly equivalent to that on conventional gilts of similar maturity.</p><p> </p><p>Three central government properties form the underlying assets which underpin the Sukuk.</p><p> </p><p>The Government was clear at the time of issuance that the Sukuk issuance was not for debt financing purposes. Instead, it was issued to deliver on the government’s commitment to become the western hub for Islamic finance. The issuance showed that the UK is open for business with all parts of the world and provided high quality capital to UK-based Islamic banks.</p><p> </p><p>UK based institutions that offer Islamic finance services are contributing to jobs and growth with assets totalling $4.5bn at the end of 2014.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","25403 ; 25555","2016-02-12T13:55:38.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449765/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449765/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Financial Services: Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many buildings in London are part of his Department's sukuk bond scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","25405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449766","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>In the Sukuk structure, rental payments provide the income for investors. When the Sovereign Sukuk were issued in July 2014 the profit rate was set at 2.036% in line with the yield on gilts of similar maturity, making the investor return on the Sukuk broadly equivalent to that on conventional gilts of similar maturity.</p><p> </p><p>Three central government properties form the underlying assets which underpin the Sukuk.</p><p> </p><p>The Government was clear at the time of issuance that the Sukuk issuance was not for debt financing purposes. Instead, it was issued to deliver on the government’s commitment to become the western hub for Islamic finance. The issuance showed that the UK is open for business with all parts of the world and provided high quality capital to UK-based Islamic banks.</p><p> </p><p>UK based institutions that offer Islamic finance services are contributing to jobs and growth with assets totalling $4.5bn at the end of 2014.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","25405 ; 25555","2016-02-12T13:55:38.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449766/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449766/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Financial Services: Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the rental income generated for investors in his Department's sukuk bond scheme is equivalent to that of the coupon paid from a June 2014 Government five-year gilt.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","25403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449767","Church Commissioners","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Diocese of Blackburn and the National Church Institutions of the Church of England do not hold these details and obtaining the information would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Church of England works with a wide variety of debt advice charities at a national and local level. Many parishes will offer space in buildings or allow debt advice surgeries to be held in their churches. Parish clergy often are the first port of call for people in need and regularly signpost individuals to where the most appropriate help and support can be found.</p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-02-05T14:36:24.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449767/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449767/answer",,,,,,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-02-02","Churches: Blackburn","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, on how many occasions buildings or parts of buildings have been made available by the Diocese of Blackburn and churches within its boundaries to (a) Christians Against Poverty and (b) other organisations providing debt counselling and employment services or campaigning against poverty.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","25287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449768","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Department does not hold information centrally on the amount or type of land held by Community Land Trusts.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-05T13:13:15.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449768/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449768/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-02","Community Land Trusts: Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of brownfield land sites in the Essex County Council area have been re-designated as community land trusts in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","25401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449769","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-10","<p>Since 2010 we have invested over £500 million to enable local authorities and the voluntary sector to support those vulnerable and at risk of homelessness. Our initiatives have included funding:</p><ul><li>Crisis – £14 million funding to support their Access to Private Rented Sector scheme, which has helped created 10,000 tenancies.</li><li>Homeless Link – over £30 million, £20 million of which went to their Homelessness Transitional Fund, which provided support to 115 areas to ensure that more rough sleepers are found quicker and given the help they need.</li><li>Help for Single Homelessness Fund – £8 million to help improve local authority support for 22,000 single homeless people.</li></ul><p>The Government has provided £470 million funding for homelessness prevention over the last Spending Review period. Salford City Council was allocated the following amounts based on the homelessness prevention funding formula within the Local Government Finance Settlement:</p><ul><li>2014-2015: £70,591</li><li>2015-2016: £70,319</li></ul><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-10T16:51:42.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449769/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449769/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-02","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which national homelessness prevention and reduction schemes received direct funding from central government (a) in 2015-16 to date and (b) in each financial year since 2009-10; and what the cost of these schemes to the public purse was in those years.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","25362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449770","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>One person without a home is one too many and we are committed to do all we can to prevent homelessness. We have protected the homelessness prevention funding local authorities receive, totalling £315 million by 2019-20. This builds on the Spending Review commitment to increase central government funding to £139 million over the next four years. We will work with homelessness organisations to consider other options, including legislation, to ensure those at risk of homelessness get earlier and more effective support.</p><p>Funding is allocated at a local authority level. Salford City Council was allocated the following amounts based on the homelessness prevention funding formula within the Local Government Finance Settlement:</p><p>- 2014-2015: £70,591</p><p>- 2015-2016: £70,319</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-11T13:18:37.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449770/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449770/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-02","Homelessness: Salford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much central government funding has been allocated to programmes in (a) Salford City Council and (b) Salford and Eccles constituency to reduce and prevent homelessness in (i) 2014-15 and (ii) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","25358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449771","Department for Communities and Local Government","true","2016-02-05","<p><del class="ministerial">In March 2015 the Greater Manchester Combined Authority contracted with the Department for a £300 million recyclable financial investment to accelerate delivery of up to 15,000 homes over 10 years. The Greater Manchester Combined Authority are aware that, in light of this contract, it will not be possible for bids from the Manchester area to be accepted for other central government housing investment programmes.</del></p><p><br /><ins class="ministerial">A £3 billion housing financial transaction programme is available over the over the next five years to support small builders and get infrastructure on large sites, this is in addition to the £300 million Manchester Housing Investment Fund. The Spending Review made £2.3 billion available to support the preparation of up to 60,000 Starter Homes by 2020. This includes £1.2 billion to prepare more brownfield land for starter homes. Further details about the use of this funding will be announced shortly. Bids from Greater Manchester will be eligible to apply for these funds in the normal way.</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-05T12:56:11.817Z","2016-02-29T10:24:41.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449771/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449771/answer","Great Yarmouth","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449771/answer/previousversion/43706","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449771/answer/previousversion/43706","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-02","Derelict Land: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will provide brownfield gap funding to bring brownfield land in Greater Manchester back into use for homes and business.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","25468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449772","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-23","<p>DCMS is responsible for transposing the EU Broadband Cost Reduction Directive, and will produce regulations to ensure the Directive comes into force by 1 July 2016. The Directive will ensure that public communications networks can request information about a broad range of physical infrastructure that may be suitable for rolling out networks, and can request access to such infrastructure on fair and reasonable terms. There will also be enhanced transparency of planned civil works and a requirement to coordinate works funded through public means.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-23T09:54:37.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449772/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449772/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Telecommunications: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what provisions the UK has adopted to comply with the new EU directive on measures to reduce the cost of deploying high-speed electronic communications networks; and how the UK plans to apply that directive in relation to new build homes.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","25477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449773","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-08","BT and the other suppliers with funding from BDUK are obliged to provide wholesale access to all new ducts and poles built using the public subsidy, in line with the requirements of the BDUK European State aid approval.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-08T13:27:00.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449773/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449773/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, to how many (a) ducts and (b) poles built with BDUK funding BT is (i) obliged and (ii) not obliged to give Wholesale Open Access to other communication providers under the terms of the BDUK state aid permission.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","25367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449774","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>Details of Ministers' and Senior Civil Servants' meetings with external organisations, including senior media figures, are published routinely and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications</a> on Gov.uk.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-09T11:37:06.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449774/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449774/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Sky","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what meetings (a) Ministers and (b) civil servants in his Department have had with (i) James Murdoch and (ii) representatives from Sky UK Limited in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","25369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449775","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-10","<p>Ministers and officials regularly meet with counterparts in other departments to discuss a range of issues. Historic records of internal government meetings are not kept.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-10T09:59:19.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449775/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449775/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Channel Four Television: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what meetings (a) Ministers and (b) officials in his Department have had with counterparts in the Cabinet Office on the privatisation of Channel 4 in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","25370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449776","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>Nearly 90% of homes and businesses in the UK currently have access to superfast broadband - and we are on target to reach 95% by the end of 2017. The Ofcom Connected Nations Report, published in December 2015 (which can be found here: <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/market-data/infrastructure/connected-nations-2015/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/market-data/infrastructure/connected-nations-2015/</a>) shows the percentage of premises that have access to broadband speeds above 10Mbit/s.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, we have substantially reduced the proportion of all UK premises with speeds less than 2Mbit/s - from 11% to around 1% in December last year. All homes and businesses that cannot currently get 2Mbps can now take advantage of a subsidised satellite broadband service delivering speeds of 10Mbps or more - meeting our commitment to provide access to at least 2Mbit/s broadband speed to all premises.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","25372","2016-02-09T13:58:03.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449776/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449776/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will estimate how many (a) households and (b) businesses do not currently reach Ofcom's acceptable minimum broadband speed of 10Mbit/s in each region and constituent part of the UK.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","25371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449777","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>Nearly 90% of homes and businesses in the UK currently have access to superfast broadband - and we are on target to reach 95% by the end of 2017. The Ofcom Connected Nations Report, published in December 2015 (which can be found here: <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/market-data/infrastructure/connected-nations-2015/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/market-data/infrastructure/connected-nations-2015/</a>) shows the percentage of premises that have access to broadband speeds above 10Mbit/s.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, we have substantially reduced the proportion of all UK premises with speeds less than 2Mbit/s - from 11% to around 1% in December last year. All homes and businesses that cannot currently get 2Mbps can now take advantage of a subsidised satellite broadband service delivering speeds of 10Mbps or more - meeting our commitment to provide access to at least 2Mbit/s broadband speed to all premises.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","25371","2016-02-09T13:58:03.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449777/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449777/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) households and (b) businesses do not have a broadband speed of 2Mbit/s in each region and constituent part of the UK.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","25372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449778","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government will launch a public consultation early next year in preparation for the implementation of a new broadband Universal Service Obligation by 2020, with the ambition to give people the legal right to request a connection to broadband with speeds of 10 Mbps, no matter where in the country they live. Almost 90% of households and businesses in the UK currently have access to superfast broadband - and we are on target for this to reach 95% by the end of 2017.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-09T11:39:26.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449778/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449778/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, by when he expects all households and businesses to have access to fibre optic broadband.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","25373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449779","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-01","<p>The government is making available a subsidy of up to £400 for each installation of satellite broadband in premises which are currently unable to access a broadband speed of at least 2Mbps throughout 2016 and 2017. The total cost of the scheme will depend on the level of demand.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-01T16:12:43.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449779/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449779/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the cost is of subsidising satellite broadband to a further one per cent of premises; and how much of that cost will be borne by each of the superfast broadband programmes.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","25374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449780","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-24","<p>The economic benefits of broadband are clear - and that is why we have done and invested more that ever since 2010 than ever to ensure that 95% of homes and businesses right across the UK will have access to superfast broadband by the end of 2017. The benefits are supported by SQW Consulting’s UK Broadband impact study in 2013 estimated that the availability and take-up of faster broadband speeds will add about £17 billion to the UK’s annual Gross Value Added (GVA) by 2024.</p><p> </p><p>In November, the Prime Minister announced our ambition to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) at 10 Mbps. This new broadband USO will give people the legal right to request an affordable broadband connection from a designated provider, up to a reasonable cost threshold, no matter where they live. We will be consulting on these proposals shortly.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-24T13:57:11.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449780/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449780/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will estimate the total annual cost to the UK economy of broadband connections that do not reach Ofcom's acceptable minimum speed of 10Mbit/s.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","25375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449781","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-08","By the end of phase two of the Superfast Broadband Programme approximately 93% of homes and businesses in Essex will have access to superfast broadband.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-08T13:28:00.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449781/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449781/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband: Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the proportion of small and medium-sized enterprises in Essex that will have access to superfast broadband by completion of phase two of the superfast broadband programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","25406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449782","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-08","BT predominately uses existing duct and pole infrastructure in BDUK project areas, but where state funded infrastructure has been used, they report it on their website at: <a href="https://www.openreach.co.uk/orpg/home/products/ductandpolesharing/contracts/contracts/downloads/State_Aided_Infrastruture_One_Truth.xls" target="_blank">https://www.openreach.co.uk/orpg/home/products/ductandpolesharing/contracts/contracts/downloads/State_Aided_Infrastruture_One_Truth.xls</a>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-08T13:28:54.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449782/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449782/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) ducts and (b) poles have been built with BDUK funding which are (i) more than one km in length and cost more than £50,000 to build and (ii) less than one km in length and cost less than £50,000 to build.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","25365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449783","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-04","<p>The UK 2012 state aid Decision applied different wholesale access conditions to new and existing infrastructure. On new infrastructure over one km in length and costing more than £50,000 to build, BT must provide access for any purpose, while on existing infrastructure and on new infrastructure less than one km in length or costing less than £50,000 to build, the primary use must be retail services (with business services only permitted where it supports the primary objective.) Both cases exceed what is required by Ofcom under regulation.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-04T12:36:48.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449783/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449783/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the state aid approval in relation to BDUK requires BT to provide Wholesale Open Access to other communication providers for ducts and poles built with BDUK funding which are (i) over one km in length and cost more than £50,000 to build and (ii) less than one km in length and cost less than £50,000 to build.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","25366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449784","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-15","The Minister for Culture and the Digital Economy met with Paul McGuinness, Roy Foster and Sir Donnell Deeny in September to discuss the bequest left by Sir Hugh Lane to the National Gallery. The department has received no other representation concerning the bequest.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-15T09:28:03.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449784/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449784/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","National Gallery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what representations he has received concerning paintings left by Sir Hugh Lane to the National Gallery.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","25304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449785","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 1 February 2016 to Question 24067 to the hon. Member for Romford (Mr Rosindell).</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-08T16:22:29.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449785/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449785/answer","Hansard Extract 1 February 2016 HOC 24067.docx","Hansard Extract 1 February 2016 HOC 24067.docx","Armed Forces: Death","Armed Forces: Death","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449785/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Armed Forces: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent steps he has taken to reduce the incidence of death during armed forces training.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","25268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449786","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) funded the first stage of a trial at Cardiff University to develop a treatment programme for ill Gulf veterans. Unfortunately there were difficulties with the recruitment of Gulf War veterans and the Department took the decision not to proceed with the second phase of the trial.</p><p>The MOD has made no assessment of the recovery outcomes for ill Gulf War veterans that took part in that trial.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","25281","2016-02-08T16:20:33.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449786/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449786/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Gulf War Syndrome: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 21 January 2016 to Question 22264, what research his Department has funded into rehabilitative therapies for veterans with persistent symptoms associated with Gulf War illnesses; and what the main findings of that research are.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","25280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449787","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) funded the first stage of a trial at Cardiff University to develop a treatment programme for ill Gulf veterans. Unfortunately there were difficulties with the recruitment of Gulf War veterans and the Department took the decision not to proceed with the second phase of the trial.</p><p>The MOD has made no assessment of the recovery outcomes for ill Gulf War veterans that took part in that trial.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","25280","2016-02-08T16:20:33.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449787/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449787/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Gulf War Syndrome: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 21 January 2016 to Question 22264, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on recovery outcomes for ill Gulf War veterans of the research that his Department has funded into rehabilitative therapies for such veterans.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","25281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449788","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>The future operational capacities of the UK Armed Forces are set out in the Strategic Defence and Security Review. Should there be a requirement for new military operations against Daesh beyond Syria and Iraq, these would need to be balanced against the commitments at the time and the capabilities available.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-05T14:25:19.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449788/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449788/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Islamic State: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the operational capacity of the (a) Royal Navy and (b) RAF to extend military operations against ISIL/Daesh beyond Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449789","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>Since 26 January UK Reapers have been deployed on intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance operations in Iraq and Syria.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-05T13:20:29.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449789/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449789/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2016 to Question 23171, to which countries RAF Reaper drones have been deployed on intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance sorties since 26 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449790","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my right hon. Friend, the then Minister for the Armed Forces (Mark Francois), on 23 June 2014 (Official Report, column 99W), to the hon. Member for West Bromwich East (Tom Watson).</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-02-05T12:52:10.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449790/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449790/answer","Hansard_extracts_Unmanned_Air_Vehicles_HOC_198710[1].docx","Hansard_extracts_Unmanned_Air_Vehicles_HOC_198710[1].docx","20140623-Hansard extract on Unmanned Air Vehicles","20140623-Hansard extract on Unmanned Air Vehicles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449790/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2016 to Question 23290, for what reasons he will not make it his policy that the House be given the opportunity to debate any decision to deploy UK Reaper aircraft outside of Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449791","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-10","<p>The UK and US have routine discussions on all aspects of US visiting forces in the UK.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-10T17:27:19.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449791/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449791/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","USA: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions his Department has had with the US administration on the siting of a US drone operation centre at (a) RAF Lakenheath, Suffolk and (b) other UK locations.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","25312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449792","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Defence Equipment and Support organisation decided to cease displaying radioactive material hazard warning signs on vehicles carrying special nuclear materials in July 2011. Before implementing this decision we sought legal advice and notified the regulator. The change was implemented in 2012 in anticipation of the transition to a single type of vehicle for the transport of both nuclear weapons and special nuclear materials and was needed in order to maintain the policy to neither confirm nor deny the presence of nuclear weapons. No changes were required to operating arrangements as a result of this decision. The Ministry of Defence's arrangements for the safe transport of defence nuclear materials include the provision of information to the emergency services in the event of an incident; this does not rely on displaying radioactive material hazard warning signs.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","25317 ; 25332 ; 25333 ; 25334","2016-02-09T16:23:47.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449792/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449792/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Radioactive Materials: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whose decision it was to cease displaying radioactive material hazard signs on vehicles carrying special nuclear materials.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","25316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449793","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Defence Equipment and Support organisation decided to cease displaying radioactive material hazard warning signs on vehicles carrying special nuclear materials in July 2011. Before implementing this decision we sought legal advice and notified the regulator. The change was implemented in 2012 in anticipation of the transition to a single type of vehicle for the transport of both nuclear weapons and special nuclear materials and was needed in order to maintain the policy to neither confirm nor deny the presence of nuclear weapons. No changes were required to operating arrangements as a result of this decision. The Ministry of Defence's arrangements for the safe transport of defence nuclear materials include the provision of information to the emergency services in the event of an incident; this does not rely on displaying radioactive material hazard warning signs.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","25316 ; 25332 ; 25333 ; 25334","2016-02-09T16:23:47.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449793/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449793/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Radioactive Materials: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on what date the decision to cease displaying radioactive material hazard signs on vehicles carrying special nuclear materials was made.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","25317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449794","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I gave on 3 February 2016 to Question 24361 and on 1 February 2016 to Question 24213, to the hon. Member for Islington South and Finsbury (Ms Thornberry).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-02-09T16:30:58.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449794/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449794/answer","20160203_QnA_extract_Tornado_Aircraft_Safety_Measures[1].docx ; 20160201_QnA_extract_on_European_Fighter_Aircraft[1].docx","20160203_QnA_extract_Tornado_Aircraft_Safety_Measures[1].docx ; 20160201_QnA_extract_on_European_Fighter_Aircraft[1].docx","24361-QnA extract on Tornado Aircraft ; 24213-QnA extract on European Fifhter Aircraft","24361-QnA extract on Tornado Aircraft ; 24213-QnA extract on European Fifhter Aircraft","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449794/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Military Aircraft: Safety Measures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) Tornados and (b) Typhoons are fitted with the TCAAS II Collision Warning System.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449795","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>No assets from the Ministry of Defence took part in the rescue of the MV Verity on 29 January 2016. There were no Royal Navy ships in the immediate vicinity.</p><p>His Netherlands Majesty's Ship De Ruyter responded while in the area undergoing training and assisted the Royal National Lifeboat Institution.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-09T16:25:00.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449795/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449795/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","MV Verity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which assets of his Department took part in the rescue of MV Verity on 29 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449796","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>We have deployed a small number of military personnel serving as liaison officers in Saudi headquarters to provide insight into Saudi operations. They remain under UK command and control. These liaison officers are not involved in the targeting process - whether it be the selection, decision making or directing.</p><p>British personnel are not involved in carrying out strikes, directing or conducting operations in Yemen or selecting targets and are not involved in the Saudi targeting decision-making process.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-05T13:21:46.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449796/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449796/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether British military advisers have been present in control rooms of the Saudi-led coalition engaged in conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","25327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449797","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Defence Equipment and Support organisation decided to cease displaying radioactive material hazard warning signs on vehicles carrying special nuclear materials in July 2011. Before implementing this decision we sought legal advice and notified the regulator. The change was implemented in 2012 in anticipation of the transition to a single type of vehicle for the transport of both nuclear weapons and special nuclear materials and was needed in order to maintain the policy to neither confirm nor deny the presence of nuclear weapons. No changes were required to operating arrangements as a result of this decision. The Ministry of Defence's arrangements for the safe transport of defence nuclear materials include the provision of information to the emergency services in the event of an incident; this does not rely on displaying radioactive material hazard warning signs.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","25316 ; 25317 ; 25333 ; 25334","2016-02-09T16:23:47.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449797/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449797/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Radioactive Materials: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what changes to operating arrangements were made as a result of the decision to cease displaying radioactive material hazard signs on vehicles carrying special nuclear materials to ensure that relevant information is available to emergency services in the event of an accident.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","25332"
