"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449913","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-05","<p>The information requested is not available as information on treatment is not recorded centrally.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-05T14:40:45.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449913/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449913/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people (a) nationally and (b) in Hull undergoing dialysis (i) applied for and (ii) were awarded personal independence payment in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","25458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449914","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Department publishes historic benefit expenditure and caseload data consistent with the annual Budget and Autumn Statements. These are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015</a></p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-08T11:31:35.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449914/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449914/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-02","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department paid out in attendance allowance in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","25323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449915","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-10","<p>As funding for the new Work and Health Programme will be devolved in Scotland, by definition it will be for the Scottish Government to decide how many people it chooses to support through their devolved programme.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-10T13:29:29.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449915/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449915/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-02","Employment Schemes: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people the £7 million fund for Employability in Scotland will assist in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","25331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449916","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>Later this year, the Government will consult on giving more responsibility to support older people with care needs to Local Authorities in England and to Wales, including people who, under the current system, would be supported through Attendance Allowance. Work on the consultation is progressing with the relevant departments, and officials will work with stakeholders throughout the consultation process.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","25279","2016-02-09T10:10:58.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449916/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449916/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-02","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with ministerial colleagues and local government representatives on transferring responsibility of attendance allowance to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","25278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449917","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>Later this year, the Government will consult on giving more responsibility to support older people with care needs to Local Authorities in England and to Wales, including people who, under the current system, would be supported through Attendance Allowance. Work on the consultation is progressing with the relevant departments, and officials will work with stakeholders throughout the consultation process.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","25278","2016-02-09T10:10:58.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449917/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449917/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-02","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what progress he has made on the transfer of responsibility for attendance allowance to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","25279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449918","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-10","<p>In Q3 2015 household debt fell to 142 per cent of household income, down from its peak of 168 per cent in Q1 2008. The Government’s plan for a higher wage, lower welfare society makes it easier for families and working people to save, and includes the new National Living Wage which will mean a pay boost for 1.7 million workers this year.</p><p> </p><p>Nonetheless, the Government recognises that there are those who face problem levels of debt. The Money Advice Service (MAS) is responsible for the coordination of publically funded free to client debt advice and is financed by a levy on the financial services industry. MAS is currently consulting on its business plan; it has proposed levying for a constant debt advice budget for 2016/17 providing around £45 million.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is currently reviewing how the public provision of free-to-client, impartial financial guidance, including consumer debt advice services, should be structured. The Public Financial Guidance consultation closed in December 2015 and the Government will report back by budget.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, we have created the independent Financial Policy Committee within the Bank of England, to ensure emerging risks and vulnerabilities across the financial system as a whole, including in relation to household debt, are identified, monitored and effectively addressed.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","25302","2016-02-10T12:34:49.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449918/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449918/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to reduce levels of family debt; and what assessment he has made of current tends in those levels.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","25270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449919","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-09T10:07:25.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449919/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449919/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-02","Social Security Benefits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit claimants, from which areas, have been asked to attend medical assessment appointments in Edinburgh by Atos due to a lack of appointments available in Glasgow; and how many benefit claimants are currently being assessed at (a) the Edinburgh centre and (b) the Glasgow centre.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","25313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449921","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) headquarters at 1 Victoria Street, London accounts for around 10% of total employees across the BIS Group. In addition, a number of our Partner Organisations, such as the Insolvency Service and Companies House, have offices in London, as well as regional offices across the country.</p><p> </p><p>By 2020 the majority of employees in BIS and its Partner Organisations will continue to be based outside London through a number of centres – such as in Birmingham, Glasgow, and Swindon – as well as a regional footprint for the provision of local services.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-10T16:49:21.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449921/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449921/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent estimate he has made of the proportion of his Department's civil service workforce based in London (a) at present and (b) at the end of the BIS 2020 restructure programme.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449922","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>As part of the Department’s change programme, BIS2020, we anticipate reducing the number of our locations from more than 80 to approximately 7 centres plus a regional footprint. Beyond the announcement made about our Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place on 28 January, we do not yet know exactly which sites will be retained or closed over the course of the Parliament. By 2020 the majority of employees in BIS and its Partner Organisations will continue to be based outside London through a number of centres – such as in Birmingham, Glasgow, and Swindon – as well as a regional footprint for the provision of local services.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-10T16:12:13.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449922/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449922/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department will have a regional hub in every region of the UK once the BIS 2020 restructuring programme is complete.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449923","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) allocates the Student Opportunity Fund to Higher Education providers as part of the teaching grant. Although the different elements of the fund are calculated on the basis of the number of students within an institution with particular characteristics, institutions have been able to use the funding in whichever way they feel is most appropriate for their students. Therefore, there is no centrally collected data on the numbers of students supported by the fund.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-29T09:50:05.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449923/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449923/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Student Opportunity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2016 to Question 22794, how many beneficiaries of the Student Opportunity Fund there were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","25508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449924","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-05","<p>Statistics showing the number of English applicants awarded Maintenance Grants are published annually by the Student Loans Company (SLC) in the Statistical First Release ‘<em>Student Support for Higher Education in England</em>’.</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p>Data provided by the SLC indicates that there were: (a) 1,720 applicants from Warrington, and (b) 760 applicants from Warrington North, awarded Maintenance Grants in the academic year 2014/15. An awarded applicant will only receive payments once SLC have received confirmation from the applicant’s provider that the student has been registered on the course.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-05T14:30:36.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449924/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449924/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Students: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many people in (a) Warrington and (b) Warrington North constituency are in receipt of student maintenance grants.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","25419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449925","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-24","<p>The roll-out of superfast broadband in Gloucestershire is being delivered by Fastershire which is a partnership between Gloucestershire County Council and Herefordshire Council with funding from central government’s BDUK programme matched by the local authorities. Over 68,000 homes and businesses in Gloucestershire and Herefordshire have access to superfast broadband which will increase to over 119,000 by September 2017.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-24T14:00:37.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449925/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449925/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband: Gloucestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment he has made of the extent of the coverage of high-speed broadband in Gloucestershire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","25423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449926","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-05","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>To date Dorset LEP has received £88.3m in funding (£79m from the Local Growth Fund and £9.3m from the Growing Places Fund) to support investment in schemes that drive local economic growth, along with £1.88m in grants.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-05T14:51:46.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449926/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449926/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Economic Growth: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the terms are of the Dorset Growth Deal; and how much funding from the public purse has been provided to the Dorset Local Enterprise Partnership.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","25497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449927","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-05","<p>Regional trade statistics at the constituency level are not available. Data showing the value of exports of goods from firms registered for VAT in Wales to the EU, the US and China in each year of the last six years are available from the HM Revenue and Customs’ Regional Trade Statistics database.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-05T14:50:00.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449927/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449927/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Exports: Cardiff South and Penarth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate the value of exports from firms based in Cardiff South and Penarth constituency to (a) the EU (b) the US and (c) China in each year of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","25533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449928","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>On 8 December 2015, at a meeting with Ministers, representatives of leading insurers committed to pass on savings to consumers through lower premiums following the implementation of Government reforms. The Government will be monitoring the industry’s reaction to these reforms closely.</p><p>The meeting on 8 December 2015 was the first Ministerial meeting with insurers to discuss the reforms announced in the Autumn Statement on 25 November. Lord Faulks subsequently met representatives from the claimant lawyer sector at the end of January 2016. Officials had previously met with both insurers and claimant lawyer representatives to discuss the reforms.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","25415","2016-02-05T14:49:36.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449928/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449928/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer to the Question 21806 of 19 January 2016, on personal injury: compensation, whether the meeting on 8 December 2015 was the first meeting of Ministers  with insurance industry representatives on reform of personal injury claims since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449929","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Department of Business, Innovation and Skills HQ, as at 31 January 2016, had 93.5% of its Senior Civil Servants based in London. The majority of staff from within the BIS Group are based outside London.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-10T16:36:12.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449929/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449929/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of Senior Civil Servants in his Department are based in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449930","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-05","<p>The rules governing jury selection and composition are unaffected by the introduction of Individual Electoral Registration (IER). Potential jurors’ names are still selected at random from the electoral register.</p><p>IER means that we can prove electors are genuine for the first time and is crucial in ensuring the registers used for jury selection are as accurate as possible.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-02-05T14:27:40.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449930/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449930/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-02","Electoral Register: Juries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the effect of individual electoral registration on jury selection and composition.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","25427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449931","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-05","<p>105,845 overseas electors were registered to vote in May 2015. The marked register, which records electors who have cast their vote, is not collated centrally. It is therefore not possible to tell how many overseas electors voted at the 2015 General Election.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-02-05T14:25:56.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449931/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449931/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-02","General Election 2015: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many UK citizens resident overseas registered to vote in the 2015 general election; and how many such citizens voted in that election.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","25553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449932","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>In the Sukuk structure, rental payments provide the income for investors. When the Sovereign Sukuk were issued in July 2014 the profit rate was set at 2.036% in line with the yield on gilts of similar maturity, making the investor return on the Sukuk broadly equivalent to that on conventional gilts of similar maturity.</p><p> </p><p>Three central government properties form the underlying assets which underpin the Sukuk.</p><p> </p><p>The Government was clear at the time of issuance that the Sukuk issuance was not for debt financing purposes. Instead, it was issued to deliver on the government’s commitment to become the western hub for Islamic finance. The issuance showed that the UK is open for business with all parts of the world and provided high quality capital to UK-based Islamic banks.</p><p> </p><p>UK based institutions that offer Islamic finance services are contributing to jobs and growth with assets totalling $4.5bn at the end of 2014.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","25403 ; 25405","2016-02-12T13:55:39.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449932/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449932/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Financial Services: Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department made of the merits of other potential methods of debt insurance before authorising use of government buildings in London as security for the sukuk bonds.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","25555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449933","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-05","<p>The list of places that sent in devolution proposals was published on Friday 11th September and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/landmark-devolution-bids-submitted-from-right-across-the-country" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/landmark-devolution-bids-submitted-from-right-across-the-country</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Proposals are developed by and belong to local areas, therefore publication is a matter for individual places. Agreed devolution deal documents are published on the gov.uk website.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-05T14:06:54.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449933/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449933/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Local Government: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish details of the fiscal devolution and retention requests made to his Department in 2015; and which such requests (a) were approved and (b) are still in development and (c) were refused.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","25602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449934","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Public Contracts Regulations 2015 introduced a number of reforms to increase transparency, streamline processes and ensure prompt payment. These reforms were introduced to support all businesses, especially smaller ones. The impact of these reforms is being assessed by our Mystery Shopper service, who will publish a report on progress in due course.</p><p>Direct SME spend in central government increased from under £3 billion (direct only) in 2009-10 to over £12 billion in 2014-15 (direct spend and spend through the supply chain).</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-11T11:59:45.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449934/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449934/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-02","Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the Public Contract Regulations 2015 on small businesses.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","25433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449935","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>A full list of all the projects funded by European Regional Development Fund and European Social Fund in the North West since 2007 are provided on the GOV.UK site.</p><p> </p><p>The total value of grants awarded to organisations in the North West of England from the Seventh Framework Programme (FP7) 2007-2013 was €420,441,221 (figure correct at 11/11/2015). The total value of grants awarded to organisations in the North West under the Horizon 2020 (2014-2020) programme is €66,881,642 (figure correct at 29/10/2015). The figures for both programmes include grants that were awarded under the complementary Euratom research and training activities programme.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-10T16:31:17.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449935/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449935/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","EU Grants and Loans: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which projects in the North West have received European Commission funding in each of the last five years; and how much each such project received in each year.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","25424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449936","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Deposit Guarantee Scheme Directive (DGSD) is a single market measure to ensure that depositors are entitled to the same level of protection wherever they deposit their money, and that UK firms are not competitively disadvantaged in relation to firms in other European Economic Area (EEA) jurisdictions.</p><p>As a result of the recent strength of the pound in relation to the euro, it was necessary for the Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) to review the sterling coverage limit. On 31 December 2015, the FSCS coverage limit changed to £75,000 per person, per authorised firm. The vast majority of UK depositors are not directly affected – more than 95% of depositors are still fully protected by the FSCS after this change.</p><p>The Government brought forward legislation to ensure that the deposit protection limit was maintained at £85,000 until 31 December 2015, to ensure those depositors affected had the time to be informed of the change and to take any actions they felt appropriate. In addition, the PRA made new rules to ensure that, until 31 December 2015, depositors with more than £75,000 worth of deposits at a single authorised firm could withdraw those deposits without penalty.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has made representations to the Commission to suggest that the reviews of the coverage level in non-euro states should occur after the Commission completes its review of suitability of the coverage level as a whole and also that changes for non-euro states reflect genuine, very large and lasting changes in exchange rates.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-10T13:04:22.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449936/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449936/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Financial Services Compensation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the value of savings held in the UK that are no longer covered under the Financial Services Compensation Scheme as a result of changes implemented in January 2016 under an EU directive on deposit protection units; and if he will make representations to his EU counterparts on reversing the effect of that directive.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","25512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449937","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-23","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The total budget allocated for the National Living Wage advertising campaign is £4.95 million. The campaign will run until the end of April and we expect to come in under budget.</p><p> </p><p>A breakdown of anticipated costs for the National Living Wage campaign can be found in the table below:</p><p><em> </em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em>Advertising design and planning</em></p></td><td><p>£497,571</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Poster advertising</em></p></td><td><p>£751,612.69</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>TV and video on demand(VOD)</em></p></td><td><p>£1,730,387.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Social media advertising (combined budget)</em></p></td><td><p>£354,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Digital display advertising and pay per click (PPC) </em></p></td><td><p>£520,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Newspaper/magazine advertising</em></p></td><td><p>£250,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>National Living Wage website</em></p></td><td><p>£21,860</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Other elements of the campaign (please specify)</em></p></td><td><p><ul><li>Radio: £299,826</li><li>Evaluation £250,000</li></ul></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Government’s new National Living Wage is a step up for working people, so it is important workers know their rights and that employers pay the new £7.20 from April 1 this year. Britain deserves a pay rise and as a One Nation Government we are making sure it gets one. The campaign will tell people about their entitlements and is targeted at employers, and workers currently earning the National Minimum Wage.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-23T15:51:38.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449937/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449937/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Living Wage: Publicity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much was spent on each media type for 2016 Step Up to the Living Wage campaign.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","25523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449938","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-05","<p>An HMRC consultation on proposals to reform the LCF closed on 10 June 2015. The proposals were developed by a government-sector working group including representatives of landfill site operators and those receiving LCF funding. The government response to this consultation is available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/reform-of-the-landfill-communities-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/reform-of-the-landfill-communities-fund</a></p><p> </p><p>The impact of the changes to the LCF announced following this consultation, at Autumn Statement 2015, is set out in <em>Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015: policy costings</em>. This document is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spending-review-and-autumn-statement-2015-documents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spending-review-and-autumn-statement-2015-documents</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-05T14:05:05.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449938/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449938/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what consultation his Department held on the proposal to withdraw the Contributing Third Payment element of the Landfill Communities Fund; and what assessment he has made of the financial ability of landfill operators and donors to continue with the scheme if that proposal is implemented.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","25529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449939","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Chancellor keeps all taxes under review as part of the fiscal process.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-10T16:39:15.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449939/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449939/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-02","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government has commissioned research on the fiscal impact of an additional tax on soft drinks containing sugar.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","25440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449943","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-10","<p>The seven devolution deals that the Government has agreed will give local leaders direct control over the levers of growth in their economies, including new powers and substantial budgets ranging from transport, to adult skills, to long term investment funds. The size of these funds is substantial, for example the West Midlands will receive over £1 billion of additional investment. It will be for mayors and local leaders to set ambitions for growth and job creation as a result of these deals. By giving local areas control over key policies and resources, and making sure that local government more efficient, effective and as possible, devolution deals will give these places the tools that they need to drive forward growth for the benefit of the whole local economy.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-10T17:04:09.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449943/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449943/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-02","Local Government: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the average benefit to local economies of devolution deals.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","25393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449944","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-10","<p>The authorities have consulted on a number of strategic options and the evidence used to produce them. I understand that the consultation is still open to interested parties and the authorities are asking local residents, businesses, land owners and developers to identify sites that they think could be suitable for housing or employment development.</p><p>As I previously set out, it is the responsibility of each authority to ensure that any Development Plan Document is prepared in accordance with its Statement of Community Involvement which should explain how they will engage local communities and other interested parties in producing development plan documents and determining planning applications.</p><p>I also refer the hon. Member to the answer given to him on of 4 February, PQ 24412.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-10T16:45:17.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449944/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449944/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-02","Regional Planning and Development: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he has powers to require the Greater Manchester Combined Authority to recommence the consultation on the sites identified in the draft Greater Manchester Spatial Framework Development Plan; and what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the current process.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","25439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449945","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-05","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework is clear that good design is indivisible from good planning and should contribute to making places better for people. Our planning guidance reinforces this strong focus on design, and provides advice on tools for delivery – including design codes.</p><p>All new homes also have to meet building regulations’ requirements. The Government has introduced new optional building regulations which means that for some requirements such as on access, local planning authorities can apply a higher standard than the national minimum requirements, where justified by need and provided that the viability of development is not compromised. The Government has also introduced a national space standard which local authorities can apply where justified by need and provided that the viability of development is not compromised.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-05T12:57:38.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449945/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449945/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-02","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that local planning authorities maintain high homebuilding standards in large sustainable urban extensions.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","25413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449946","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-08","<p>Up to September 2015, over 128,000 homes had been purchased with assistance of Help to Buy Equity and Mortgage Guarantee Loans.</p><p>Since 2010/11, over 53,000 thousand tenants have purchased their homes through Right to Buy (and preserved Right to Buy for housing association tenants). The voluntary scheme extending to housing associations will give 1.3 million more families the opportunity to do this.</p><p>The Department publishes statistics on Help to Buy and Right to Buy at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-communities-and-local-government/about/statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-communities-and-local-government/about/statistics</a></p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-08T17:40:55.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449946/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449946/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-02","Home Ownership Incentive Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many homeowners have accessed (a) Help to Buy and (b) Right to Buy.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","25518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449947","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-05","The Government is committed to supporting S4C and values its service to Welsh speaking audiences. In order for S4C to continue to provide a first-class service and have a sustainable future, the Government announced (on Wednesday 3rd February) an extra £400,000 funding for 2016/17 and the intention to carry out a comprehensive review in 2017.<p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-05T16:14:22.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449947/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449947/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","S4C","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will ensure that he consults with S4C before any future agreement is reached with any third party affecting that company's budget.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","25425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449948","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-03","<p>BT and other suppliers with funding from BDUK are obliged to provide wholesale access to all new ducts and poles built using public subsidy, in line with the requirements of the BDUK European State aid approval.</p><p><br> Communications providers report on the details of the infrastructure they access to local authorities and devolved administrations, who are responsible for managing Broadband Delivery UK (BDUK) contracts.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-03T16:20:08.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449948/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449948/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many BDUK funded (a) ducts and (b) poles are currently being accessed by communications providers other than BT.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","25426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449949","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Government wants to ensure Channel 4 has a strong and secure future, and is looking at a broad range of options, including those put forward by channel 4. This work is ongoing.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-26T16:19:41.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449949/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449949/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Channel Four Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the value of Channel 4.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","25535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449950","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","true","2016-02-11","<p>The visual arts are a very important part of the UK's wider cultural and creative industries sectors and employ 1.8 million people. According to the latest set of government statistics published last month, the value of sectors categorised under 'artistic creation' - which include the visual arts - between 2010 and 2014 was<del class="ministerial"> £9,355,000.</del> <ins class="ministerial">£9.35 billion.</ins></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-11T10:06:13.18Z","2016-02-12T11:44:10.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449950/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449950/answer","Wantage","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449950/answer/previousversion/44983","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449950/answer/previousversion/44983","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-02","Visual Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the economic value of the visual arts sector was in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","25479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449951","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The European Commission has not yet set a date for a periodic review of ARR. When this happens, the Intellectual Property Office will draw on existing material and consult afresh with its stakeholders for the latest evidence to inform the review.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-09T17:22:44.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449951/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449951/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-02","Art Works: Copyright","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department plans to take in preparation for the European Commission's review of the Artist's Resale Right.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","25480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449952","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>Any credible concerns or evidence relating to the possibility of civilian casualties caused by air strikes may be submitted to the Ministry of Defence Ministerial Correspondence Unit, Main Building, Whitehall, London, SW1A 2HB, or by email to ParliBranch-Treat-Official@mod.uk</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-09T16:25:45.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449952/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449952/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Military Intervention: Casualties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2016 to Question 23581, who the best official is to contact with credible reports from an external organisation of civilian casualties.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","25515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449953","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"><p> </p></td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>It is the long standing policy of the Government not to comment on Special Forces.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-08T16:21:10.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449953/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449953/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Military Alliances: Special Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans his Department has for the introduction of two tier special forces in the Joint Force 2025 announced in the Strategic Defence and Security Review involved in training, assistance advice and mentoring to UK partners.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449954","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>An armed conflict was occurring in Syria at the time of the air strike on 21 August 2015. The UK's military strike was governed by international humanitarian law.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-02-05T13:18:51.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449954/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449954/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-02","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2016 to Question 23435, whether it is his Department's position that the UK was a party to the armed conflict occurring in Syria at the time of the air strike on 21 August 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","25545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449955","Department for Education","false","2016-02-10","<p>There are strict rules protecting publicly funded school land. This is set out in published guidance, which is available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/protection-of-school-playing-fields-and-public-land-advice" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/protection-of-school-playing-fields-and-public-land-advice</a></p><p>A copy of the guidance has been placed in the House Library.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-10T12:01:19.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449955/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449955/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-02","Schools: Property Transfer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, by what process a local authority seeking to dispose of school land can obtain Ministerial permission for development.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","25441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449956","Department for Education","false","2016-02-05","<p>Information on care leavers in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015, who were aged 19, 20 and 21 in 2013 and 2014 is not available. However, the information for care leavers aged 19, 20, or 21 in 2014 and 2015 is shown in the tables below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Accommodation type<sup>2</sup></strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>All care leavers aged 19, 20 or 21</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Of which, number that were former unaccompanied asylum seeking children¹</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Suitable</strong></p></td><td><p>20,570</p></td><td><p>21,010</p></td><td><p>240</p></td><td><p>550</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Unsuitable</strong></p></td><td><p>1,660</p></td><td><p>1,840</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>40</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: SSDA903</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>All care leavers aged 19, 20 or 21 with whom the local authority were in touch</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Of which, number that were former unaccompanied asylum seeking children¹</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>21,980</p></td><td><p>22,520</p></td><td><p>260</p></td><td><p>590</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: SSDA903</p><p>Numbers have been rounded to the nearest 10.</p><ol><li><p>This includes young people who were unaccompanied asylum seeking children in their final period of care.</p></li><li><p>Suitability of accommodation is not recorded where the young person has gone abroad, been deported or where their residence is not known.</p></li></ol>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","25346","2016-02-05T13:44:01.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449956/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449956/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-02","Care Leavers: Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many care leavers in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015 who were aged 19, 20 or 21 in 2013 and 2014 and housed in accommodation considered (i) suitable and (ii) unsuitable were former unaccompanied asylum-seeking children looked after by the local authority.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","25428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449957","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-05","<p>Data on the number of smart electricity and gas meters installed is set out in the Government’s ‘Smart Meters, Great Britain, Quarterly report to end September 2015’, published on 22 December 2015:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-release-and-data-smart-meters-great-britain-quarter-3-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-release-and-data-smart-meters-great-britain-quarter-3-2015</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The roll-out is making good progress with more than 2 million meters now operating under the Programme.</p><p> </p><p>Data is not collected from energy suppliers in a format that allows details of the number of smart meters installed in London or each London borough to be produced.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-05T12:43:25.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449957/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449957/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-02","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many smart (a) electric and (b) gas meters have been installed in (i) London and (ii) each London borough since the smart meter programme started.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","25416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449959","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Government has invested significant resources into research and development to assess how we can reduce the impact caused by bats in churches. This has included a three year research project that concluded in 2013, as well as a pilot project led by Historic England that focused on churches with significant bat issues. Natural England is currently creating a licensing framework to provide the mechanism through which the impact of bats will be controlled in churches.</p><p>A partnership of five organisations, including the Church of England and Natural England, is seeking Heritage Lottery Funding for a five year project to support the creation of a national support network for churches that have bat related issues. The outcome of the bid for funding will be known in March.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-05T07:32:59.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449959/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449959/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-02","Bats: Churches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress has been made by her Department on developing a toolkit for effective and safe management of bats in churches as recommended in the University of Bristol report on Management of bats in churches, a pilot, published in January 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","25554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449960","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-05","<p>My Rt. Hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, launched the Great British Food Unit during a visit to Weetabix on 21 January 2016. This unit brings together experts from Defra and UKTI and will celebrate British food, encourage innovation and increase the number of Protected Food Names. The unit will increase investment and exports by opening new global markets and offering support to companies.</p><p> </p><p>Weetabix is made with locally sourced wheat and its iconic cereal is eaten in 80 countries. It is an historic British business benefitting from foreign investment and so provided an excellent example of the various types of business the Food Unit is there to support.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-05T13:41:45.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449960/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449960/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-02","Food: Marketing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the purpose was of her recent visit to Weetabix in Burton Latimer; and what progress has been made on the launch of the Great British Food Unit.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","25421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449961","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) discussed human rights with Prime Minister Modi during Mr Modi’s visit to the United Kingdom in November 2015. Mr Modi reassured the Prime Minister and honourable members in his address to Parliament that he fully respected India’s traditions of tolerance and diversity. I raised the extensive interest taken by right honourable and honourable members in this place with the Indian High Commissioner on 12 January. The Indian Constitution provides for a judiciary which is independent of the legislature and the executive. The courts have proved to be a powerful medium of progressive change in India and a protector of India’s Constitution, challenging successive governments on various issues, including human rights. However, we do acknowledge that there is a backlog of cases and are encouraged by discussions in India to address this issue.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-10T16:46:50.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449961/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449961/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","India: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Indian counterpart on alleged human rights violations in that country; and what progress has been made on promoting a fair and independent judicial system in India.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","25494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449962","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-10","In 2014 there were 255 officers in full time language training with an additional 332 officers and/ or spouses attending part time language classes. In 2015 there were 332 officers in full time language training and 767 officers/spouses following part time language classes. To provide statistics for the years 2006-2013 would incur disproportionate costs.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-10T14:07:50.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449962/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449962/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","Foreign and Commonwealth office: Languages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many officials in his Department have undertaken Foreign and Commonwealth Office language classes in each year from 2006.","true","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","25525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449963","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-05","<p>I have had no recent discussions with opposition parties in Iran. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office works across the region with a range of stakeholders in support of regional security.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-05T12:23:45.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449963/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449963/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","Iran: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with democratic opposition parties in Iran; and what his Department's policy is on working with opposition parties to achieve greater political stability in that region.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","25513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449964","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-05","<p>The UK Government recognises that conscientious objection can be regarded as a human right under Article 18 of the International Convention on Civil and Political Rights. The UK co-sponsored a UN Human Rights Council resolution on conscientious objection to military service in 2013. It is important that all states live up to their international obligations to protect freedom of thought, conscience and religion. The UK Government does not specifically monitor respect for conscientious objection in individual countries.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-05T14:31:11.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449964/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449964/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","Conscientious Objectors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which of the countries listed in the Human Rights and Democracy Report have been highlighted as lacking respect for conscientious objection; and what representations he has made to his counterpart in each such country on this matter.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","25509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449965","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>Bahrain has had a de facto moratorium in place on the use of the death penalty since 2010, although we are concerned a number of individuals have received the death penalty sentence since then. The UK opposes the death penalty around the world because we believe it undermines human dignity, there is no evidence that it works as a deterrent and any error made in its application is irreversible. We regularly discuss human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) raised human rights with his Bahraini counterpart, Sheikh Khalid Bin Ahmad Al Khalifa at their last meeting on 4 February.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T14:18:30.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449965/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449965/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","Bahrain: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in the Bahraini authorities on the planned execution of Mohammad Ramadan and Hussain Moosa.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","25517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449966","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-12","<p>We are aware of reports of alleged violations of International Humanitarian Law (IHL) by actors to the conflict and take these very seriously. It is important that all sides conduct thorough and conclusive investigations into all incidents where it is alleged that IHL has been breached. As the Saudis themselves announced on Sunday, they have mechanisms in place to investigate alleged incidents and to learn lessons if things go wrong. The Ministry of Defence also monitors incidents of alleged IHL violations using available information, which in turn informs our overall assessment of IHL compliance in Yemen. At this stage, looking at all the information available to us, we have not assessed that there has been a breach of IHL by the coalition, but continue to monitor the situation closely, seeking further information where appropriate.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-12T11:43:56.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449966/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449966/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of whether there have been any unintentional violations of international humanitarian law carried out by Saudi coalition forces in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","25397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449968","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>The UK is not a member of the Saudi Arabia-led military Coalition. British personnel are not involved in carrying out strikes, directing or conducting operations in Yemen or selecting targets, and are not involved in the Saudi targeting decision-making process. We have deployed a small number of military personnel serving as liaison officers in Saudi Arabia's headquarters to provide insight into Saudi operations. They remain under UK command and control.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T14:05:19.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449968/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449968/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether UK personnel were involved in checking the target selections for any (a) deliberate and (b) unintended breaches of international humanitarian law during the recent Saudi Arabian military action in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","25398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449969","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>Records show that up until the end of 2015, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office had officers with a C1 pass in the following languages:<br>Albanian, Arabic, Bosnian, Bulgarian, Czech, Dari, Dutch, Farsi, French, Georgian, German, Greek, Hebrew, Hindi, Hungarian, Indonesian, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Macedonian, Mandarin, Pashtu, Polish, Portuguese, Romanian, Russian, Serbian, Slovene, Spanish, Swedish, Thai, Turkish and Vietnamese.</p><p>The FCO Language Centre was re-opened in September 2013 to renew the focus and investment in languages as a core diplomatic skill to ensure that we get the right people with the right skills in the right jobs to deliver our foreign policy objectives. The Language Centre gives us a strong platform to grow our language skills as an organisation and develop a pipeline of talent to fill language slots on a continuous basis.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T14:15:35.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449969/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449969/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Languages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 23665, in which 33 different languages his Department has Operational Level (C1) examination pass speakers employed in the last five years up to the end of 2015.","true","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","25483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449970","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-10","<p>Records from the last five years show that the Foreign and Commonwealth Office has 51 officers who have a current Operational Level (C1) Arabic pass and 44 officers with a C1 pass in Mandarin/ Cantonese. We only record current C1 passes, valid for five years after the date of the exam, and therefore do not have pre-2010 data.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-10T14:09:34.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449970/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449970/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-02","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Languages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 23665, how many (a) Arabic speakers with an Operational level (C1) examination pass and (b) Mandarin/Cantonese speakers there were employed in his Department in each year since 2006.","true","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","25484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449971","Department of Health","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Government is committed to making the full £1.4 billion investment available over the course of this Parliament to improve mental health services for children and young people.</p><p> </p><p>In line with guidance published by NHS England, all clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have produced Local Transformation Plans (LTPs) for children and young people’s mental health and these have all now been assured and funding allocated for implementation. These plans required all key partners to agree locally how best to meet the mental health needs of children and young people in their local populations and should cover the whole spectrum of need, which includes improving access to mental health services for vulnerable groups such as children in care and care leavers so that they can receive high quality mental health care when they need it. It is for local partners to decide how much of the funding which will be allocated to CCGs to improve local services throughout the five years will be spent specifically on children in care and other vulnerable groups. However, this will be based on an assessment of local needs and set out in the LTPs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s overall strategy to improve outcomes for care leavers is set out in the <em>Care Leaver Strategy: A cross-departmental strategy for young people leaving care</em> report (October 2013), and a one-year-on document, <em>Care Leaver Strategy: One year on progress update</em>, (October 2014) that reported on progress made and set out how the Government intends to further improve support for care leavers. The Government intends to publish its refreshed Care Leaver Strategy later this year.</p><p> </p><p>The Local Government Association has produced a spreadsheet giving details of every LTP can be found using the following webpage address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/camhs" target="_blank">www.local.gov.uk/camhs</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","25482","2016-02-10T13:05:27.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449971/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449971/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Mental Health Services: Care Leavers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve access to mental health services for care leavers aged 18 to 25 years old.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","25481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449972","Department of Health","false","2016-02-05","<p>There is no simple solution to reducing infections in hospitals or the wider health economy. Thus as part of implementation of the UK 5 Year Antimicrobial Resistance Strategy 2013 – 2018, a wide ranging programme of work is already underway to reduce the incidence of infections. The Strategy is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-5-year-antimicrobial-resistance-strategy-2013-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-5-year-antimicrobial-resistance-strategy-2013-to-2018</a></p><p> </p><p>Plans are in hand to strengthen local leadership and reporting to support the drive to reduce healthcare associated infections. There are national evidence based guidelines for preventing healthcare associated infections and local and national surveillance to help us identify areas where more focused attention and effort is needed are part of this programme. Our expert scientific advisory committee is currently evaluating relevant data to identify interventions that can be used to reduce infections such as <em>Escherichia coli</em> blood stream infections.</p><p> </p><p>In addition a new indicator will bring together data into one website to help the National Health Service understand that cleanliness, infection prevention and control and antibiotic usage are linked issues which require urgent coherent action. This will support our aim of ensuring local delivery and more information will be in the second Strategy progress report due to be published in the spring.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","25407 ; 25408","2016-02-05T12:24:42.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449972/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449972/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Infectious Diseases: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve infection control in primary health trusts.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","25382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449973","Department of Health","false","2016-02-05","<p>In the United Kingdom, testing for Zika virus is carried out in the Public Health EnglandRare and Imported Pathogens Laboratory at Porton Down. In the event of a positive result, the clinicians caring for the patient are informed immediately, as well as local Public Health officials. The clinicians will be referred to the national guidance for further advice on management and follow-up. The majority of people (roughly 80%) infected do not have symptoms. For those with symptoms, <a href="http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/_layouts/forms/Publication_DispForm.aspx?List=4f55ad51-4aed-4d32-b960-af70113dbb90&amp;ID=1413" target="_blank">Zika virus generally causes a mild, short-lived (2 to 7 days) illness</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In the case of a pregnant woman, the guidance suggests referral to a fetal medicine service for further assessment, including an ultrasound scan. Samples will also be tested for other infections prevalent in the geographical region that the patient has visited, and which may present with similar symptoms, such as dengue.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-02-05T12:59:13.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449973/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449973/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Zika Virus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what protocol is in place in the event of a person in the UK testing positive for the Zika virus.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","25417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449974","Department of Health","false","2016-02-10","<p>An expert group has been looking at how we can improve access to rapid diagnostic testing as part of the implementation of the UK Antimicrobial Resistance Strategy. The group is currently formulating its conclusions and intends to start working with stakeholders to implement improvements across the system from 2016; a part of this work will include an economic analysis to support the rapid adoption of new tests.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has been feeding this work into the Accelerated Access Review, which will make recommendations to Government on speeding up access to transformative new medicines and technologies, including diagnostics, for National Health Service patients. The review is due to report in April 2016.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-10T15:34:19.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449974/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449974/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Infectious Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the most effective way to implement the use of rapid diagnostic technology for the purpose of accurately diagnosing infections in hospitals.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","25383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449975","Department of Health","false","2016-02-10","<p>Health Education England (HEE) is responsible for the management of medical specialty recruitment on behalf of the four United Kingdom countries.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested for 2016 is not yet available.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>HEE publishes application to place ratios in October on an annual basis. The August to December 2016 data will be published in October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Competition ratios for 2015 can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://specialtytraining.hee.nhs.uk/specialty-recruitment/competition-ratios/2015-competition-ratios/" target="_blank">http://specialtytraining.hee.nhs.uk/specialty-recruitment/competition-ratios/2015-competition-ratios/</a></p><p> </p><p>To note: The data used to determine the competition ratios for is drawn from the initial recruitment round and does not include re-advertisements.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-10T15:37:46.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449975/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449975/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Doctors: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the application-to-place ratio prior to interview is for ST1/CT1 posts starting in August to December 2016 at each specialities national recruitment office.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","25389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449976","Department of Health","false","2016-02-05","<p>Monitor and the NHS Trust Development Authority (NHS TDA) (becoming NHS Improvement from 1 April 2016) engage with National Health Service trusts and foundation trusts on a daily basis and staff regularly meet with these organisations to review and support their plans to improve their financial positions.</p><p> </p><p>Since 15 January, senior representatives have met with seven trusts for face to face meetings and have also attended events, with a number of trusts represented, to discuss the 2015/16 financial year and financial planning for 2016/17. In addition, senior representatives have also met with NHS Providers to discuss these issues and fed into their communications to the provider sector on these topics.</p><p> </p><p>All trusts will be submitting draft financial plans for 2016/17 to Monitor and the NHS TDA in due course. Monitor and the NHS TDA will continue to engage further with trusts as appropriate.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-05T12:29:49.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449976/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449976/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many meetings have taken place between NHS Improvement and NHS trusts to agree plans to improve their financial position since 15 January; which providers have had such meetings with NHS Improvement; and when each such meeting took place.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","25603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449977","Department of Health","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Government is committed to making the full £1.4 billion investment available over the course of this Parliament to improve mental health services for children and young people.</p><p> </p><p>In line with guidance published by NHS England, all clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have produced Local Transformation Plans (LTPs) for children and young people’s mental health and these have all now been assured and funding allocated for implementation. These plans required all key partners to agree locally how best to meet the mental health needs of children and young people in their local populations and should cover the whole spectrum of need, which includes improving access to mental health services for vulnerable groups such as children in care and care leavers so that they can receive high quality mental health care when they need it. It is for local partners to decide how much of the funding which will be allocated to CCGs to improve local services throughout the five years will be spent specifically on children in care and other vulnerable groups. However, this will be based on an assessment of local needs and set out in the LTPs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s overall strategy to improve outcomes for care leavers is set out in the <em>Care Leaver Strategy: A cross-departmental strategy for young people leaving care</em> report (October 2013), and a one-year-on document, <em>Care Leaver Strategy: One year on progress update</em>, (October 2014) that reported on progress made and set out how the Government intends to further improve support for care leavers. The Government intends to publish its refreshed Care Leaver Strategy later this year.</p><p> </p><p>The Local Government Association has produced a spreadsheet giving details of every LTP can be found using the following webpage address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/camhs" target="_blank">www.local.gov.uk/camhs</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","25481","2016-02-10T13:05:27.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449977/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449977/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Mental Health Services: Children and  Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he is planning to allocate a proportion of the proposed £1.4 billion mental health funding for children and young people over the next five years funding to be invested in mental health services to support (a) children in care and (b) care leavers.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","25482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449978","Department of Health","false","2016-02-10","<p>Sir Bruce Keogh, NHS England’s Medical Director, has undertaken a review of the National Clinical Director (NCD) resource designed to focus clinical advisory resources on areas where major programmes of work are currently being taking forward, or areas identified as priorities for improvement. As a result of the review, NHS England has proposed to change the way in which clinical advice is received in speciality areas in the future.</p><p> </p><p>Where there will no longer be a specific NCD role, NHS England will secure expert clinical advice from its Clinical Networks and through its relationships with professional bodies and by appointing clinical advisors. For neurology it is planned that access to advice will be through clinical leads and members of the NHS England-funded neurology clinical networks, the Neurology Clinical Reference Group and Royal Colleges. It is expected that these new arrangements will be in place from 1 April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Neurology Intelligence Network (NIN) is a joint partnership programme between Public Health England (PHE) and NHS England to support the generation and dissemination of neurology related health intelligence. PHE currently funds the on-going design, development and management of the NIN.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-02-10T13:02:47.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449978/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449978/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Neurology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which National Clinical Director will be responsible for overseeing the neurology intelligence network from March 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","25394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449979","Department of Health","false","2016-02-05","<p>Public Health England undertakes monitoring of healthcare associated infections, which includes the mandatory healthcare associated infections surveillance system. These arrangements are regularly reviewed and changes introduced in 2015 include enhanced surveillance for very antibiotic resistant infections (carbapenemase-producing Enterobacteriaceae).</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-05T12:22:18.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449979/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449979/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Hospitals: Infectious Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he made of the potential merits of expanding the monitoring of healthcare-associated infections.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","25411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449980","Department of Health","false","2016-02-10","<p>The United Kingdom pharmaceutical industry will play a leading role in the development of a vaccine for the Zika virus, in collaboration with a range of the UK’s infectious disease experts, who are world leaders in this area.</p><p> </p><p>In the Spending Review, the £1 billion Ross Fund, run jointly by the Department of Health and Department for International Development, includes over £350 million for the development of new vaccines, drugs and diagnostics for infectious diseases.</p><p> </p><p>Particularly noteworthy within this, the UK Vaccine Network, with up to £120 million of funding, brings together industry, academia and Government to finance the development of new vaccines for priority infectious diseases with epidemic potential, including Zika. Indeed, the Network will launch a major funding call to finance the development of vaccines for Zika and other priority diseases at the end of February.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-02-10T17:17:39.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449980/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449980/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Zika Virus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what role the UK pharmaceutical industry is playing in the development of a vaccine for the Zika virus.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","25387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449981","Department of Health","false","2016-02-10","<p>We have not made an assessment of the annual cost of prescription charges to those with cystic fibrosis. However, there are a number of prescription charge exemptions in place, for which someone with cystic fibrosis may qualify. These include exemptions based on low income, such as certain out of work benefits and the NHS Low Income Scheme, and age. Where someone does not qualify for exemption, Prescription Prepayment Certificates are available. The three-month and 12-month certificates allow someone to claim as many prescriptions as they need for £29.10 and £104, respectively.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-10T13:23:40.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449981/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449981/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Cystic Fibrosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the annual cost of prescription charges paid by adults with cystic fibrosis; what the effect of prescription charges is on such adults; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","25392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449982","Department of Health","false","2016-02-05","<p>With regards to the National Health Service in Scotland, as healthcare is a devolved issue, the Department cannot comment.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England commissions specialised neurological services at a national level, including those with muscle-wasting conditions. The neurosciences service specification sets out what designated specialised providers must have in place to offer evidence-based, safe and effective care. Patients should have access to a multidisciplinary team (MDT) to assess, diagnose and provide support. The MDT will include neuromuscular consultants, neuromuscular physiotherapists, psychologists, specialist nurses, occupational therapists, speech and language therapists and other health professionals.</p><p> </p><p>The specification further sets out that neuromuscular clinics need to identify those at risk of respiratory problems and refer for specialist respiratory assessment and monitoring.</p><p> </p><p>The specification can be found at the following link:</p><p>www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/d04-neurosci-spec-neuro.pdf</p><p><br> A separate specification covers services for children.</p><p><br> <a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/e09-paedi-neurology.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/e09-paedi-neurology.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","25339 ; 25340","2016-02-05T14:35:18.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449982/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449982/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress his Department has made on improving access to specialist psychology support for people with muscle-wasting conditions.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Mr David Crausby","25514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449984","Department of Health","false","2016-02-05","<p>The (NHS England South) Regional Quality Surveillance Group is responsible for ensuring that all the national recommendations outlined in NHS England’s report on the death of William Mead are implemented.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will be keeping track of progress on this front.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-05T12:27:36.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449984/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449984/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","William Mead","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the national recommendations outlined in NHS England's report on the death of William Mead are implemented.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","25551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449985","Department of Health","false","2016-02-05","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health asked Public Health England (PHE) to review the evidence and make recommendations on the scope for a public-facing campaign to raise awareness of Sepsis. PHE will publish its evidence-based review shortly.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-05T12:25:55.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449985/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449985/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Sepsis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will instigate a national public awareness campaign about sepsis.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","25552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449986","Department of Health","false","2016-02-05","<p>Ministers have not yet made any official representations to other Government departments about the proposed changes to housing benefit for tenants in supported housing. Neither has the Department made any formal estimates of the people likely to be affected by the proposed changes. However, discussions are ongoing at official level between Departments.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","25548","2016-02-05T12:17:06.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449986/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449986/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-02","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people (a) with mental health conditions, (b) with long-term disabilities and (c) who receive social care who will be affected by the planned cap on housing benefit for tenants in supported housing.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","25549"
