"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449999","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-04","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-04T11:40:01.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449999/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449999/answer","25524 FINAL.pdf","25524 FINAL.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Polygamous Marriages","UKSA Letter to Member - Polygamous Marriages","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449999/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-02","Polygamy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate his Department has made of the number of men in the UK who are in polygamous marriages.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","25524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450000","Home Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) provides a formal monthly performance report to the Home Office and Home Office Ministers. This includes updates on the performance of police forces in meeting the Service Level Agreement (SLA) standards for the time taken to complete local disclosure checks.</p><p>The DBS monitors the performance of all police disclosure units and works closely with any force, including the Metropolitan Police Service (MPS), not meeting its targets. An MPS Gold Group is overseeing the recovery plan in place at the MPS and Home Office officials maintain a close oversight of the progress being made by assessing weekly reports and through regular attendance at the Group.</p><p>It is a priority of the MPS, DBS and the Home Office to see improvements as quickly as possible and I will continue to monitor the situation closely.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-09T16:00:42.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450000/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450000/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-02","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what reports she has received from (a) the Metropolitan Police and (b) other police forces of delays in processing Disclosure and Barring Service applications; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","25396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450001","Home Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government has no plans to place an unnecessary bureaucratic burden on locally elected Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) or Chief Constables by requiring this information to be reported centrally. Decisions about the most effective use of available resources, including the number and operating hours of police stations and the number of custody cells, are a matter for the Police and Crime Commissioner and Chief Constable locally (the Mayor’s Office for Policing and Crime and the Commissioner in the case of the Metropolitan Police and the Corporation and the Commissioner in the case of the City of London Police), tailored to the needs of the local community.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-09T09:07:51.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450001/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450001/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-02","Police Stations: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 12 June 2015 to Question 1705, if she will make it her policy to collate information centrally on the number of police stations and police custody cells that closed.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","25435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450002","Home Office","false","2016-02-05","<p>On 21 July 2015 the Home Secretary met a group of MPs, a Welsh Assembly Member, Michael Mansfield QC and members of the Orgreave Truth and Justice Campaign (OTJC), led by Louise Haigh MP, to discuss their calls for a public inquiry to be established following the publication of the IPCC scoping review into the policing of events at Orgreave in 1984.</p><p>Following this meeting, on 15 December 2015 the Home Secretary received a submission from the OTJC containing their arguments for establishing a public inquiry into the events at Orgreave. That 85 page submission raises a range of extensive issues which the Home Secretary is currently considering fully and in detail before responding. She will set out the Government’s position in due course.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","25399","2016-02-05T15:56:30.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450002/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450002/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-02","Orgreave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the implications are for her Department's policies of the legal submission given to her on 15 December 2015 by the Orgreave Truth and Justice Campaign on the confrontation between police and miners at Orgreave in June 1984.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","25414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450003","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-05","<p>DFID’s £2 million funding to the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) in Libya was given in response to their 2015 Budget Extension Appeal. The ICRC will submit to DFID, in accordance with agreed ICRC standard reporting timelines, an Annual Report, Financial Report and Annual Audited Accounts by June 2016.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-05T14:45:46.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450003/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450003/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-02","Libya: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2016 to Question 24446, what reports her Department has received from the International Committee of the Red Cross on the spending by that body of humanitarian relief funds from her Department for humanitarian relief in Libya.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","25507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450004","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The number and causes of deaths of prisoners aged under 18 and held in the custody of the National Offender Management Service is published on a quarterly basis in the Safety in Custody Statistics Bulletin annual deaths tables (see table 1.3 at the following link) <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/495427/safety-in-custody-deaths-dec-2015.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/495427/safety-in-custody-deaths-dec-2015.xls</a>. The most recent publication was published on 28 January 2016 and contains information on deaths up to 31 December 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T16:27:08.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450004/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450004/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Youth Custody: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many under-18s died while in youth custody between 2010 and 2015; and what the causes of those deaths were.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","25493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450005","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>Prisoners recalled to custody having breached the conditions of their licence will be arrested by the police and then taken to the nearest local prison for the area in which they were arrested. Prisoners who, prior to release had been held in the closed training estate or in an open prison, will not therefore be returned to the same prison from which their release took place. Those prisoners who had been held in a local prison prior to release on licence, may be returned to the same establishment if that is the nearest local prison for the area in which they were arrested.</p><p> </p><p>Once returned to a local prison, prisoners will be re-assessed and a decision made on which prison is best suited to their needs, taking into account all factors in the case including the risks they present and other security issues. Prisoners recalled for short periods may remain in the local prison until release unless there are specific reasons, including security reasons, why they should be transferred elsewhere.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-10T11:07:09.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450005/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450005/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make it his policy to send prisoners returned to jail having broken their licence conditions to a different prison than the one from which they were released.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","25492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450006","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>Prisoners recalled to custody having breached the conditions of their licence will be arrested by the police and then taken to the nearest local prison for the area in which they were arrested.</p><p> </p><p>Once returned to a local prison, prisoners will be searched and risk assessed in line with the prisons’ local policy for stopping contraband. Prisons deploy a comprehensive range of robust searching and security measures to detect items of contraband, both at the point of entry to the prison and concealed within the prison. We will continue to explore new methods of preventing drugs coming into prisons</p><p> </p><p>Prisoners found with drugs on entry to prison are sanctioned, potentially including days added to their sentence, or, in cases where the quantity of drug or packaging suggests possession with intent to supply, will be referred to the police. All visitors or staff caught with drugs are referred to the police.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-10T14:56:04.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450006/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450006/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number of prisoners returned to jail having broken their licence conditions and subsequently been found to be carrying concealed drugs.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","25491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450007","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>The information below records the number of offenders convicted under Terrorism Act (TACT) legislation in each calendar year since 1 January 2013 who had previously served a custodial sentence. Information prior to 2013 is not available.</p><p> </p><p>In 2013, 25 offenders were convicted of TACT offences, none of which had previously served a custodial sentence.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014, 17 offenders were convicted of TACT offences, of which 1 had previously served a custodial sentence.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, 37 offenders were convicted of TACT offences, of which 2 had previously served a custodial sentence.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-02-05T14:44:05.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450007/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450007/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people convicted of a terrorism offence had previously served a custodial sentence in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450008","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>Where injury to prison officers is suspected to be wholly due or due in part to new psychoactive substances, this is noted but the figures are subjective and the connection with NPS cannot be proven. We are piloting mandatory drug testing for new psychoactive substances from this month, and intend to roll it out to all prisons by April 2016.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-10T11:02:29.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450008/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450008/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number of prison officers injured on duty in incidents involving new psychoactive substances in the last year.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","25488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450009","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","25490","2016-02-09T17:35:20.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450009/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450009/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prison Officers: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number of hospital visits made by prison officers in each of the last 12 months as a result of incidents involving new psychoactive substances.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","25489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450011","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","25489","2016-02-09T17:35:20.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450011/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450011/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number of prison officer hours spent guarding prisoners in hospital as as a result of incidents involving new psychoactive substances.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","25490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450012","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>Information on prosecutions for fraudulent whiplash claims is not held centrally, and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Government remains concerned about the number and cost of personal injury claims and the impact they have on motor insurance premiums. At 760,000 (of which 690,000 were for whiplash) in 2014/15, personal injury motor claims volumes are still at historically high levels, being some 50% higher than in 2006 when there were around 520,000 such claims.</p><p>The Insurance Fraud Taskforce published their final report on 18 January which was supportive of the Government’s proposals to tackle fraudulent and unnecessary claims. The Government will consider their recommendations closely.</p><p>The Association of British Insurers regularly publishes data on the number of detected fraudulent claims made, and the most recent published data can be found here: <a href="https://www.abi.org.uk/News/News-releases/2015/07/You-could-not-make-up-Savings-honest-customers-insurers-expose-3-6-million-worth-insurance-frauds" target="_blank">https://www.abi.org.uk/News/News-releases/2015/07/You-could-not-make-up-Savings-honest-customers-insurers-expose-3-6-million-worth-insurance-frauds</a></p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","25418","2016-02-09T15:50:24.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450012/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450012/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number of whiplash claims each year which are fraudulent; and if he will place in the Library the evidence used to produce this estimate.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","25531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450013","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Court Proceedings Database shows how many defendants were prosecuted and convicted for each offence in a given year. It does not show what percentage of those were prosecuted and convicted following their involvement in group offending; or what role each person played within the enterprise. Such information is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-05T14:31:20.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450013/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450013/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Aiding and Abetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been convicted under joint enterprise in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450014","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) deploys a comprehensive range of robust searching and security measures to detect items of contraband both at the point of entry to the prison and concealed within the prison. NOMS continues to explore new methods of preventing drugs coming into prisons and body scanners are seen as a valuable part of this strategy.</p><p> </p><p>An independent expert panel is assessing the use of a body scanner at HMP Wandsworth, as required by the Justification of Practices Involving lionising Radiation Regulations 2004.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","25486","2016-02-10T17:54:42.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450014/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450014/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his Department's policy is on investing in drug detection technology to tackle illicit substances being brought into prisons; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","25485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450015","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-05","<p>On 8 December 2015, at a meeting with Ministers, representatives of leading insurers committed to pass on savings to consumers through lower premiums following the implementation of Government reforms. The Government will be monitoring the industry’s reaction to these reforms closely.</p><p>The meeting on 8 December 2015 was the first Ministerial meeting with insurers to discuss the reforms announced in the Autumn Statement on 25 November. Lord Faulks subsequently met representatives from the claimant lawyer sector at the end of January 2016. Officials had previously met with both insurers and claimant lawyer representatives to discuss the reforms.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","25534","2016-02-05T14:49:36.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450015/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450015/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Insurance Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 19 January 2016 to Question 21806, what commitment he received from insurance industries that savings from government reforms would be passed on to consumers; and what steps he plans to take to ensure that such commitments are monitored and transparent.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450016","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) deploys a comprehensive range of robust searching and security measures to detect items of contraband both at the point of entry to the prison and concealed within the prison. NOMS continues to explore new methods of preventing drugs coming into prisons and body scanners are seen as a valuable part of this strategy.</p><p> </p><p>An independent expert panel is assessing the use of a body scanner at HMP Wandsworth, as required by the Justification of Practices Involving lionising Radiation Regulations 2004.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","25485","2016-02-10T17:54:42.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450016/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450016/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he expects to have body scanners to help detect illicit substances installed in prisons.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","25486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450017","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>We take a zero tolerance approach to drugs in prison and there are already a range of robust measures in place to detect drugs, including the use of search dogs and intelligence-led searches.</p><p> </p><p>We recently introduced tough new laws which will see those who smuggle packages over prison walls, including new psychoactive substances, face up to two years in prison. We are piloting mandatory drug testing for new psychoactive substances from this month, and intend to roll it out to all prisons by April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Those who involve themselves in the distribution of drugs in our prisons should know that they will face prosecution and extra time behind bars.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-10T10:58:05.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450017/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450017/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to prevent new psychoactive substances being used among the prison population.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","25487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450018","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The contracts with Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) contain robust provisions requiring CRCs to ensure that its workforce is competent and adequately trained. Contracts with the 21 CRCs have been published and can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search/Results?Keyword=3190-3-Reducing%20Reoffending&amp;LocationType=AllLocations" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search/Results?Keyword=3190-3-Reducing%20Reoffending&amp;LocationType=AllLocations</a></p><p>As I said in my response to question 23959, our contract management teams closely monitor and robustly manage providers to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to maintain service delivery, reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T15:37:36.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450018/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450018/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February to Question 23959, what contractual commitments are included in contracts with community rehabilitation companies to ensure maintenance of a minimum level of staffing.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450019","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>Information on prosecutions for fraudulent whiplash claims is not held centrally, and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Government remains concerned about the number and cost of personal injury claims and the impact they have on motor insurance premiums. At 760,000 (of which 690,000 were for whiplash) in 2014/15, personal injury motor claims volumes are still at historically high levels, being some 50% higher than in 2006 when there were around 520,000 such claims.</p><p>The Insurance Fraud Taskforce published their final report on 18 January which was supportive of the Government’s proposals to tackle fraudulent and unnecessary claims. The Government will consider their recommendations closely.</p><p>The Association of British Insurers regularly publishes data on the number of detected fraudulent claims made, and the most recent published data can be found here: <a href="https://www.abi.org.uk/News/News-releases/2015/07/You-could-not-make-up-Savings-honest-customers-insurers-expose-3-6-million-worth-insurance-frauds" target="_blank">https://www.abi.org.uk/News/News-releases/2015/07/You-could-not-make-up-Savings-honest-customers-insurers-expose-3-6-million-worth-insurance-frauds</a></p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","25531","2016-02-09T15:50:23.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450019/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450019/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been prosecuted for bringing fraudulent claims in whiplash cases in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","25418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450020","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>Of those prisoners who escaped in 2014/15, the most recent period for which figures are available, none are currently listed as having a conviction for an offence committed during the period that they were unlawfully at large.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T16:30:51.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450020/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450020/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisoner Escapes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January to Question 23624, how many offences were committed by prisoners who had escaped in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","25436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450021","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-01","<p>I refer the honourable member to the answer given to PQ 23624 on 26<sup>th</sup> January 2016.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-01T11:53:07.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450021/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450021/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prisoner Escapes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January to Question 23624, how many offences were committed by prisoners who had absconded in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","25437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450022","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>It has not been possible to answer this question within the time available. I will write to the hon. Member as soon as possible.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T17:03:35.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450022/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450022/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Prison Officers: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2016 to Question 24637, how many Band 3 and above prison officers took severance or redundancy packages in each month since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","25478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450023","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Minimising and Managing Physical Restraint (MMPR) system has been rolled out across the youth secure estate with the exception of Feltham Young offender Institution (YOI), which goes live at the end of February 2016 and Parc YOI, which goes live by the end of this year.</p><p> </p><p>MMPR will also be rolled out to the under -18 secure escort service for Secure training Centres and Secure Children’s Homes, and will go live in April 2016.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T16:53:14.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450023/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450023/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Restraint Techniques","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the national roll-out of the minimising and managing physical restraint system is to be fully completed and implemented.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","25391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450024","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Youth Justice Board (YJB) is responsible for commissioning and placing all young people under-18 in a suitable secure establishment.</p><p> </p><p>Following the welcome and continued reduction in the number of young people in custody, the YJB has been able to reduce the number of commissioned places across the secure estate. However, as the number has reduced so those who remain tend to be those who have been arrested for the most violent crimes and who pose the greatest difficulties for those who care for them.</p><p> </p><p>Although decommissioning will affect the number of places available in the secure estate, young people are placed in establishments that can most effectively manage their individual needs and risks. Factors such as age, suitability of regime, closeness to home, risk of self-harm or to others, and other risk factors are all been taken into account when placing a young person in custody.</p><p> </p><p>Restraint should only be used against young people as a last resort where it is absolutely necessary to do so, when young people are putting their own safety and the safety of others at risk, and where no other form of intervention is possible or appropriate. We are committed to closely monitoring the independently assessed Minimising and Managing Physical Restraint system, including through an ongoing analysis of its effectiveness.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the effects of decommissioning on staff numbers within the youth secure estate is not available centrally and can only be collected at disproportionate costs.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T16:48:05.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450024/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450024/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-02","Youth Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect of decommissioning sites where children could be detained on (a) the mix of children in custody, (b) the implementation of the Minimising and Managing Physical Restraint system and (c) staff numbers.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","25390"
